    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Stitches that are taken back into the material where the thread was last drawn through in a running stitch. In plain sewing, back stitches strengthen a running. This stitch is also used in embroidery to create outlines of patterns.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000036731/Caulfeild and Saward, Encyclopedia of Victorian Needlework (1972)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>行針往返刺縫的針法。回針縫可使平針縫更為牢固。刺繡時，亦可以此針法鏽出圖案的輪廓。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052784/TELDAP database (2009-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Steken waarbij de naald telkens wordt ingestoken op de helft van de voorgaande steek. Bij nuttige handwerken gebruikt men achtersteken om rijgsteken te versterken. In de borduurkunst gebruikt men achtersteken ook om patronen te creëren.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
